  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "The legal history of money laundering prohibitions is complex and developed gradually over several decades. Here's an overview of key developments:\n\n1. Early Precursors (Pre-1970s):\n- Some financial reporting requirements existed to track potential criminal proceeds\n- Limited legal frameworks addressing financial crime concealment\n\n2. United States Bank Secrecy Act (1970):\n- First comprehensive legislation targeting financial transaction reporting\n- Required banks to report large cash transactions\n- Established foundation for modern anti-money laundering (AML) regulations\n\n3. International Developments (1980s):\n- Vienna Convention (1988) - First international treaty criminalizing drug money laundering\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established in 1989\n- Increased international cooperation against financial crimes\n\n4. Major Expansion (1990s):\n- U.S. Money Laundering Control Act (1986)\n- Comprehensive legal frameworks developed globally\n- Expanded criminal penalties and reporting requirements\n- International standards for tracking suspicious transactions\n\n5. Post-9/11 Developments:\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001)\n- Enhanced regulations targeting terrorist financing\n- Significantly expanded reporting and compliance requirements\n\n6. Ongoing Global Regulatory Evolution:\n- Continuous refinement of international AML standards\n- Increased technological sophistication in tracking financial transactions\n\nThis progression represents a gradually expanding legal approach to combating financial crimes.",
